  "prompt": "I just bought an Activa 110 cc bike and technicians have advised me against riding it above 40 kmph until the first 750 km. Why is that so?",
  "response": "The advice to keep your new Activa 110 cc below 40 kmph for the first 750 km is part of a process called \"engine break-in\" or \"running-in.\" Here\u2019s why this is important:\n\n1. **Settling of Engine Components**:\n   - New engines have moving parts (piston rings, cylinders, bearings, etc.) that need to wear in gradually and form a proper seal. Running the engine at high speeds initially can cause excessive friction and wear, reducing the engine\u2019s lifespan and performance.\n\n2. **Heat Management**:\n   - High speeds generate more heat, and during the break-in period, the engine is not yet optimized to handle this efficiently. Running at lower speeds helps the engine operate at a manageable temperature.\n\n3. **Lubrication**:\n   - Fresh engines require time for oil to properly circulate and lubricate all components. High speeds can compromise lubrication, leading to increased wear and tear.\n\n4. **Longevity and Performance**:\n   - A proper break-in period ensures that the engine components seat correctly, which improves fuel efficiency, performance, and longevity of the bike.\n\n5. **Manufacturer Recommendations**:\n   - Most vehicle manufacturers provide specific break-in guidelines (usually in the owner\u2019s manual). Following these guidelines ensures you don\u2019t void your warranty and keeps your bike in optimal condition.\n\nBy adhering to the 40 kmph limit for the first 750 km, you\u2019ll help your Activa 110 cc achieve better performance and a longer lifespan. After the break-in period, you can gradually increase your speed and enjoy the full potential of your bike. Make sure to also change the engine oil after the break-in period as recommended, as it may contain metal particles from the initial wear.",
